{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 19:42:21.341992", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content=\"Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\nScope / context\\n- Topology: multi‑tier Clos (fat‑tree) using eBGP. Super‑spine (AS 65000) peers with all spines; spine routers peer with leaves in their pod. Each leaf advertises a /24 to the fabric. Inter‑router links use 172.16.0.0/16 /31s.\\n- Devices examined (selected): leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0, hosts pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) and pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2).\\n- Tools/commands used: host reachability (ping matrix), FRR BGP and route table outputs, host network configuration.\\n\\nExecutive summary (short)\\n- The fabric is converged and operational. BGP sessions are established and prefixes from leaf subnets are propagated throughout the network. Host connectivity between the tested hosts is functional (0% packet loss). No device exhibiting obvious failure or route withdrawal was detected in the collected data.\\n\\nChecks performed and key evidence\\n1) Host-level reachability\\n- pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: 2 transmitted, 2 received, 0% loss; rtt avg ~1.206 ms (rtt range 0.92–1.493 ms).\\n- The reachability matrix returned numerous successful tests across pods; no packet loss observed in sampled pings.\\n\\n2) Host network configuration\\n- pc_0_0:\\n  - IP: 10.0.0.2/24\\n  - Default route: via 10.0.0.1\\n- pc_0_1:\\n  - IP: 10.0.1.2/24\\n  - Default route: via 10.0.1.1\\n- Both hosts have their expected /24s and a default gateway present.\\n\\n3) Leaf/router BGP and routing tables (representative facts)\\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP table:\\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 is present as local (directly connected).\\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 is learned with multiple paths; a single best path is selected (nexthop 172.16.1.16 in this snapshot).\\n- leaf_router_0_1 BGP table:\\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 is present as local (direct).\\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 is learned (best nexthop 172.16.1.18 in this snapshot).\\n- super_spine_router_0 shows full visibility of 10.1.x/24 prefixes learned from below, and the spines/leaves show each other's /24 prefixes.\\n- Routing tables show the leaf /24s installed in the RIB/FIB (connected on the leaf that owns them; learned on others).\\n\\nObserved behavior / detailed findings\\n- BGP convergence: Tables show prefixes from leaves across the network and each router has a best path selected. Table versions and route entries indicate recent, stable convergence (routes present and active).\\n- Inter‑router next‑hop diversity: Multiple BGP paths are visible for many leaf prefixes (e.g., leaf networks appear with many alternate next‑hops such as 172.16.1.0/16 addresses). For each prefix, one best path is chosen (indicated by >). This is consistent with the Clos fabric providing multiple spine paths and is expected.\\n- Host reachability: Hosts pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 can reach each other with 0% loss and low latency. The ping matrix shows successful inter‑host communication across many pods.\\n- No route withdrawals: No BGP advertised prefixes appear to be missing; the superset of leaf /24s is present across spines and the super‑spine.\\n\\nAnomalies, faults, or suspicious items\\n- No critical anomalies identified in the collected outputs:\\n  - No packet loss in reachability tests (sampled).\\n  - No BGP session flaps or withdrawn prefixes were observed in the retrieved BGP table snapshots.\\n  - Route installation looks consistent (leaf networks are connected on the expected leaf, learned and present on remote routers).\\n- Minor observations (informational, not strictly “faults”):\\n  - Variation in selected best next‑hop for the same prefix across different leaves (e.g., leaf_router_0_0 prefers 172.16.1.16 for 10.0.1.0/24; leaf_router_0_1 prefers 172.16.1.18 for 10.0.0.0/24). This reflects path selection differences (AS‑path length/ordered next‑hop preference) across the fabric and may lead to asymmetric forwarding for some flows—this is expected in EBGP multi‑path fabrics unless policy enforces symmetry.\\n  - Some measured ICMP RTT variability in the larger ping matrix (a few samples show higher variance or a higher max RTT), but these samples still show 0% packet loss. The RTT spikes appear isolated in the samples and are not accompanied by loss.\\n\\nFault localization\\n- No device in the provided dataset showed clear signs of failure (no down interfaces reported for the examined leaf/spine/super‑spine, no missing BGP adjacencies or withdrawn routes visible).\\n- Localized connectivity: leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 each have their /24s directly connected and in the RIB/FIB — they are functioning as expected.\\n\\nRoot cause analysis\\n- Because no outages, BGP route withdrawals, or packet loss were observed, there is no root cause of a failure to identify from the collected evidence.\\n- The only notable fabric characteristic is multi‑pathness and differing selected best next‑hops across devices; this is a design/behavior attribute of the Clos/eBGP setup rather than a failure.\\n\\nSummary conclusion\\n- Network state: healthy and converged.\\n- Anomalies/faults: none identified in the provided snapshots and reachability testing.\\n- Faulty devices: none identified.\\n- Root cause for any malfunction: not applicable — no malfunction detected.\\n\\nIf you want I can:\\n- (next step) Verify BGP session/state details (show ip bgp summary / show bgp neighbors) per router to explicitly confirm adjacency states and uptime,\\n- collect interface counters or ethtool on specific interfaces if you suspect link errors,\\n- run targeted traceroutes between hosts to expose path asymmetry if desired.\\n\\n(Report contains only diagnostic observations; no mitigations or configuration changes are proposed per your instructions.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.\" additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='30a9e223-18c9-47e8-8118-06b14c6b781b'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
